In [6]:
## Loading Dataset
def load_Data(scale):
  dataGenerator = preprocessing.image.ImageDataGenerator(
    rescale = scale
  )
  dataTrain = dataGenerator.flow_from_directory(
    "/content/Data/train",
    target_size=(80,80),
    color_mode = "grayscale",
    batch_size = batch,
    class_mode = "categorical"
  )
  dataTest = dataGenerator.flow_from_directory(
    "/content/Data/test",
    target_size=(80,80),
    color_mode = "grayscale",
    batch_size = batch,
    class_mode = "categorical"
  )
  return dataTrain, dataTest

In [7]:
def build_network(output_num, activation_func):
  inp = layers.Input(shape=(80, 80, 1))
  out = layers.Flatten()(inp)
  out = layers.Dense(1024, activation=activation_func)(out)
  out = layers.Dense(1024, activation=activation_func)(out)
  out = layers.Dense(output_num, activation="softmax")(out)

  model = models.Model(inputs=inp, outputs=out)
  model.compile( optimizer=optimizers.SGD(learning_rate=0.01) , loss='categorical_crossentropy' , metrics=['accuracy'])
  return model
In [8]:
def trainPlot(history):
  fig, ax = plot_con = plt.subplots(1, 2)
  fig.set_size_inches(10, 4)  
  ax[0].plot(history.history['accuracy'], label='Train')
  ax[0].plot(history.history['val_accuracy'], label='Test')
  ax[0].set(xlabel='No. epoch', ylabel='Accuracy value', title='Accuracy of model')
  ax[0].legend(loc="lower right")

  ax[1].plot(history.history['loss'], label='Train')
  ax[1].plot(history.history['val_loss'], label='Test')
  ax[1].set(xlabel='No. epoch', ylabel='Loss value', title='Loss of model')
  ax[1].legend(loc="upper right")
  plt.show()
In [9]:
def getTrueLabels(loader):
  labels = []
  total_batchs = int(np.ceil(len(loader.classes)/loader.batch_size ) )
  print(total_batchs)
  for i in range(total_batchs):
    x,y = loader.next()
    for label in y:
      labels.append(backend.argmax(label))
  return np.array(labels)

/usr/local/lib/python3.6/dist-packages/sklearn/metrics/_classification.py:1272: UndefinedMetricWarning: Precision and F-score are ill-defined and being set to 0.0 in labels with no predicted samples. Use `zero_division` parameter to control this behavior.
  _warn_prf(average, modifier, msg_start, len(result))

There is a rough increase in evaluatinon values when we use 'tanh' as an activation function. Although, there seem to be same recall valus for macro average. This consiperancy related to the special features of each activation function. Relu function mostly used when our data includes positive numbers with great distribution. In this case, it doesnt help us to get a good accuracy. On the other side, Tanh offers us zero centered advantage which cuases better performance. In both cases, we are facing the problem with the distribution of our data and the solution is to normalization that means to rescale all of numbers in order to gather all of them between 0 and 1.

Optimizer¶

Momentum¶

In [0]:
def build_network_optimizer(output_num, activation_func, momen):
  inp = layers.Input(shape=(80, 80, 1))
  out = layers.Flatten()(inp)
  out = layers.Dense(1024, activation=activation_func)(out)
  out = layers.Dense(1024, activation=activation_func)(out)
  out = layers.Dense(output_num, activation="softmax")(out)

  model = models.Model(inputs=inp, outputs=out)
  model.compile( optimizer=optimizers.SGD(learning_rate=0.01, momentum=momen) , loss='categorical_crossentropy' , metrics=['accuracy'])
  return model

Totally, momentum is a float hyperparameter >= 0 that accelerates gradient descent in the relevant direction and dampens oscillations. In other word, this parameter helps training to go throw the right direction. As it seems, momentum can become overrated which means if the value set to big numbers the efficiency of the training can hurt and not every data can train the model.

Adam¶

In [17]:
def build_network_optimizer_adam(output_num, activation_func):
  inp = layers.Input(shape=(80, 80, 1))
  out = layers.Flatten()(inp)
  out = layers.Dense(1024, activation=activation_func)(out)
  out = layers.Dense(1024, activation=activation_func)(out)
  out = layers.Dense(output_num, activation="softmax")(out)

  model = models.Model(inputs=inp, outputs=out)
  model.compile( optimizer=optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=0.001) , loss='categorical_crossentropy' , metrics=['accuracy'])
  return model

In this example, increasing number of epochs improve accuracy, but it doesnt mean that always the more epochs we have the better aacuracy we get. Overfiting is the main problem caused by big epochs number. Model start to learn from loss data. Using suitable loss function can prevent model from overfitting.

Loss Function¶

In [0]:
def build_network_loss_MSE(output_num, activation_func):
  inp = layers.Input(shape=(80, 80, 1))
  out = layers.Flatten()(inp)
  out = layers.Dense(1024, activation=activation_func)(out)
  out = layers.Dense(1024, activation=activation_func)(out)
  out = layers.Dense(output_num, activation="softmax")(out)

  model = models.Model(inputs=inp, outputs=out)
  model.compile( optimizer=optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=0.001) , loss='mean_squared_error' , metrics=['accuracy'])
  return model

Regularization¶

In [0]:
def build_network_regularization(output_num, activation_func):
  inp = layers.Input(shape=(80, 80, 1))
  out = layers.Flatten()(inp)
  out = layers.Dense(1024, activation=activation_func, kernel_regularizer=regularizers.l2(0.0001))(out)
  out = layers.Dense(1024, activation=activation_func, kernel_regularizer=regularizers.l2(0.0001))(out)
  out = layers.Dense(output_num, activation="softmax")(out)

  model = models.Model(inputs=inp, outputs=out)
  model.compile( optimizer=optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=0.001) , loss='categorical_crossentropy' , metrics=['accuracy'])
  return model

L2 regularization penalizes the sum of the square of the weights. It transforms the values to a number close to 0, but not quite 0. According to the result, it doesnt have suitable affect on evaluation values.

Drop Out¶

In [12]:
def build_network_regularization_dropout(output_num, activation_func):
  inp = layers.Input(shape=(80, 80, 1))
  out = layers.Flatten()(inp)
  out = layers.Dropout(0.1)(out)
  out = layers.Dense(1024, activation=activation_func, kernel_regularizer=regularizers.l2(0.0001))(out)
  out = layers.Dropout(0.1)(out)
  out = layers.Dense(1024, activation=activation_func, kernel_regularizer=regularizers.l2(0.0001))(out)
  out = layers.Dropout(0.1)(out)
  out = layers.Dense(output_num, activation="softmax")(out)

  model = models.Model(inputs=inp, outputs=out)
  model.compile( optimizer=optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=0.001) , loss='categorical_crossentropy' , metrics=['accuracy'])
  return model
